  "doc_id": "36087",
  "text": "Nevertheless, there is no recent empirical support for strongly embodied and completely disembodied theories [CITATION_1] . Therefore, an important problem requiring further investigation is the degree to which conceptual representations are grounded in sensory and motor processes [CITATION_2] . The contribution of each modality in different categories of objects has been studied using the methods of multi-modal rating of objects [CITATION_3] . These data demonstrated that the majority of objects' characteristics were rated as visual. Smell and taste were relevant for a minority of objects, whereas tactile sensations and sound occupied the intermediate positions. Similar results were obtained for concept-property items when participants rated the degree to which the property could be experienced through five perceptual modalities (vision, audition, touch, smell, and taste) [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, the specificity of experience related to various senses is still unclear. This study is aimed to analyse the peculiarities of the structure of experience related to different senses through the mental reactivation of experience and its pleasantness judgment.",
